From: Q-Audion <dep.ivanov@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] FrameCryptor: AES-256-GCM when key material is 32 bytes

The AEAD already selects AES-256-GCM when the derived key is 32 bytes
(GetAesGcmAlgorithmFromKeySize). The only blocker is ParticipantKeyHandler::
SetKeyFromMaterial hardcoding the derived length to 128 bits. Derive the length
from the key-material size instead: a 32-byte shared key -> 256-bit key ->
AES-256-GCM; any other size keeps the original 128-bit behavior. The app then
chooses the cipher purely by the byte length it passes to setSharedKey() — no
Java/JNI API change. ratchet_window_size=0 (no ratcheting) so the .cc ratchet
paths are not exercised; left unchanged to keep this a single, low-risk hunk.

diff --git a/api/crypto/frame_crypto_transformer.h b/api/crypto/frame_crypto_transformer.h
--- a/api/crypto/frame_crypto_transformer.h
+++ b/api/crypto/frame_crypto_transformer.h
@@ -201,8 +201,12 @@ class ParticipantKeyHandler : public webrtc::RefCountInterface {
   void SetKeyFromMaterial(std::vector<uint8_t> password, int key_index) {
     webrtc::MutexLock lock(&mutex_);
     if (key_index >= 0) {
       current_key_index_ = key_index % crypto_key_ring_.size();
     }
+    // Q-Audion AES-256 E2EE: pick the derived encryption-key length from the
+    // key-material size. 32-byte shared key -> 256-bit key -> AES-256-GCM
+    // (GetAesGcmAlgorithmFromKeySize selects the variant by size); any other
+    // size preserves the original 128-bit behavior.
     crypto_key_ring_[current_key_index_] =
-        DeriveKeys(password, key_provider_->options().ratchet_salt, 128);
+        DeriveKeys(password, key_provider_->options().ratchet_salt,
+                   password.size() == 32 ? 256 : 128);
   }
